article.description: It was veteran Stephon Marbury against rookie Tony Parker -- and it was no contest.
article.headline: Marbury rips rookie for season-high 36 points

images.name: Marbury_Stephon 020224 inline
images.caption: Stephon Marbury of Phoenix, right, gets a pass around San Antonio's Tim Duncan. Marbury had a season-high 36 points in the Suns' victory.

article.linkText: Marbury teaches Spurs a lesson in 92-83 victory
article.story:
PHOENIX -- It was veteran Stephon Marbury against rookie Tony Parker -- and it was no contest. The cat-quick Marbury schooled the 19-year-old San Antonio guard for a season-high 36 points Sunday night, leading the Suns to a 92-83 victory and handing the weary Spurs their second road defeat in two nights. "I just had it going tonight," Marbury said after shooting 14-for-24 from the field and 8-for-8 from the foul line. He also grabbed seven rebounds and handed out seven assists. "We were playing aggressive and I was just taking what they were giving me," Marbury said. The victory was the 1,500th in the Suns' history and made them the 12th NBA franchise to reach that total. Shawn Marion added 17 points and 12 rebounds for the Suns, who won for only the second time in five games since Frank Johnson replaced Scott Skiles as coach last Sunday. Joe Johnson added 15 points as he and Marbury outscored the Suns' starting guards, Parker and Charles Smith, 51-5. Tom Gugliotta had 13 points and 10 rebounds for the Suns. David Robinson led the Spurs in scoring for only the second time this season with 25 points. Tim Duncan had 21 points and 13 rebounds, his league-leading 44th double-double in 55 games. Steve Smith had 20 points for San Antonio. San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich praised Marbury's play and chastised his team for its performance. "Stephon was a pain..." Popovich said. "He penetrated, he found people (open) very well... He did an outstanding job." That's more than Popovich could say about his own team. "Phoenix did an outstanding job of playing for four quarters," Popovich said. "I don't think we did the same. I think it's important now for us to find out how important winning is. "Not competing or making it important were huge factors and that's a big step backward in my mind. It's disappointing." Frank Johnson was thrilled with the Suns' performance. "We came out and jumped on them early and kept our composure," he said. "If we play with that emotion, that heart, we'll win a lot of games." Marbury scored 16 points in the first quarter when the Suns took a 32-15 lead. The Suns gained their big advantage with two strong runs, including a 12-0 surge in the final 3½ minutes. Marbury had six points and one assist in that late burst and had four points and an assist during an earlier 8-0 run. Marbury kept pressuring the Spurs and prevented them from getting set defensively. The Suns extended their lead to 19 points, 34-15, their biggest lead of the game, on Joe Johnson's jumper opening the second period. Duncan failed to score in the first quarter, missing all five of his field goal attempts. Gugliotta, who did a solid defensive job on Memphis rookie Pau Gasol on Thursday night, also forced Duncan into some bad early shots. Duncan picked up the pace in the second period, scoring eight points as Gugliotta got into foul trouble, committing his third personal. By halftime, the Spurs had whittled the Suns' lead to 10 points, 47-37. Robinson also got into early foul trouble, committing two in the first three minutes and did not play the rest of the first period. Marbury continued to break down the Spurs' defense in the third period, knifing his way through for 10 points as Phoenix held a 69-57 lead at the end of the quarter. In the fourth quarter, San Antonio got as close as three points twice, the last time at 84-81 on a layup by Smith with 2:11 remaining. However, Marbury took charge again, hitting two free throws and a jumper in the last two minutes and feeding Gugliotta for a long jumper. Game notes
The Suns' Penny Hardaway missed his second consecutive game because of tendinitis in his left knee. ... The teams meet again Tuesday night at San Antonio. ... Phoenix has not reached the 100-point mark in its last 10 games. ... The Spurs beat the Suns 105-93 in their first meeting in America West Arena on Dec. 14 when Duncan had 32 points and 19 rebounds. ... Joe Johnson and Milt Palacio played their first games at home since the Suns acquired them in a trade with Boston on Wednesday.
